name: Victory Point
notes: Good espresso in a board game cafe.

name: My Coffee Roastery
notes: Fairytale cottage coffee shop, with incredible attention to detail. Look out for sorted jars of bad coffee beans ("floater" and "immature" among others).

name: The Coffee Movement
notes: Favorite coffee shop in SF! Bonus points if you go in the summer and they have a repurposed orange VW van for people to sit in.

name: Apple Visitor Center
notes: Coffee: slightly average. Apple's HQ being across the street: kinda surreal. If you get a foamy drink, there's a nice litte surprise at the top :)

name: HITW
notes: Essentially a coffee window with a few squeaky tables around it on the street, but few coffee experiences beat getting an espresso shot, reading a book and taking in the beautiful North Beach SF neighborhood, especially in early fall.

name: Crown Coffee Lab
notes: Coffee meets tasting menus: get their sample of 3 coffees and nerd out over tasting notes. Also offers classes, consultations and a podcast!

name: Nirvana Soul
notes: Great coffee in a pink, tropical-themed shop. The staff is incredibly friendly and it shows: the shop even has a coffee Spotify playlist!

name: Sextant Coffee Roasters
notes: Some of the best coffee the Bay Area has to offer.

name: Bicycle Coffee
notes: Bike-themed shop geared towards cyclists. Expect to be served with both coffee and cycling gear if interested. They give you discounts if you show them your helmet!

name: Awaken
notes: Downtown Oakland spot with pretty good espresso and oversized beach lounging chairs in front of the shop that let you people-watch and bask in the sun.

name: Hal's Office Coffee
notes: Neighbor-ly spot in Albany: get their empanadas and an espresso and thank me later!

name: SPRO
notes: Coffee truck alert!

name: **Tony's Pizza Napoletana
notes: The other pizza spot in my top 2. Incredibly popular but also fully deserves all its hype. Props for getting creative with the pizza: I loved the jam-flavored one I got.

name: **Gregoire
notes: The notorious potato puffs with truffle oil. Non-optional and highly craveable.

name: Casa Barotti
notes: Among the only Italian streetfood spots in the Bay. Choose a few small slices from their selection and enjoy.

name: **Cheeseboard
notes: Worker-owned and operated pizza place with vegan ingredients and a new veggie-based set of toppings each day. One of Berkeley's landmarks and hugely influential in food movements.

name: Third Culture Bakery
notes: Mochi donuts! Can't go wrong with any flavor since they'll always be the perfect mix of chewy and crunchy.

name: **Oma San Francisco Station
notes: Omakase spot hidden at the edge of a Japantown mall. Relatively affordable and amazing sushi and service.

name: **Mochill Mochi Donuts
notes: Very crave-inducing mochi donut spot. My favorite is the black sesame which is a great mix of chewy-ness and flowery-looking donut.

name: Daily Driver
notes: Bagel shop that gets creative with its recipes: I got the goat cheese and honey cinammon raising bagel and enjoyed it in their airy space in the Dogpatch.

name: La Mar Cebicheria Peruana
notes: Famous Peruvian spot, with some of the best nigiri I've had. Very fresh and tasty, and a great balcony area overlooking the Bay Bridge and Embarcadero.

name: Top Dog
notes: Simple hot dog spot a block and a half from UC Berkeley's campus. The perfectly simple recipe of a bun, hot dog and mustard served in a place that has been there since 1966.

name: Besharam
notes: Great Gujarati cuisine with menu sections named after cities: for me, Khaman (lentil cake with coconut chutney) and their house-made cocktails were the hightlight of the experience.

name: Zachary's Chicago Pizza
notes: Local legend pizza place that serves Chicago-style pizza with yummy stuffings. Once the pizza is ready, the friendly staff will offer to serve you the first piece. The spinach and mushroom  is a classic!

name: Ralph's
notes: Interesting experience in this Ralph Lauren coffee shop. The decor was fancier than the coffee, but still not your usual drink.

name: Cafe Grumpy
notes: Cute spot in a Whole Foods (convenient). The espresso was pretty good as well!

name: %Arabica
notes: Great coffee in an awesome location: get your coffee to go and walk over to the park overlooking the Manhattan skyline.

name: Black Fox Coffee
notes: Fave NYC coffee spot! Singular attention to making very high quality coffee drinks provides for some of the best espresso I've had. Checkout one of their three spots around New York, but I recommend their Pine Street flagship.

name: Cafe Patoro
notes: Quaint shop in the Front Street historical district. You'll enjoy the calm atmosphere if you like a cozy spot to read, write or meet up with the shop's regulars. Also pretty good coffee is a bonus.

name: Coffee Project
notes: Deconstructed coffees are the star of the show at this small coffee shop. Give it a try for a different and revealing coffee experience in which your typical latte with come as 3 separate cups.

name: Cortaditos
notes: Cuban coffee shop with lively decor and music. Get one of their signature drinks and enjoy the happy atmosphere.

name: Joe Coffee Company
notes: Coffee kiosk in Bryant Park. My recommendation is to get a coffee and drink it slowly taking in the sounds and sights of the city seeping in at the edges of this urban park.

name: Hungry Ghost
notes: Their Fulton St Brooklyn location makes for a nice neighbor-ly coffee experience. My recommendation: take your drink to go and walk around the street lined with bookstores and cafes, a nice getaway from the bustle of Manhattan visible from the distance.

name: Devocion
notes: Some of the best coffee in NYC: at their Brooklyn location you can enjoy a glass-roofed coffee room with stage-like seating.

name: Lillo Cucina Italiana
notes: Tiny cash-only pasta spot with only a handful of tables. Can't go wrong with any of the dishes and the Italian decor and the friendliness of the people dining creates a heart-warming food atmosphere!

name: YUBU
notes: Innovative food items in this casual Korean spot: get a set of their 3 sushi-like small eats. I recommend the salmon and spicy tuna.

name: L'Industrie
notes: NYC style pizza at its best. The burrata and truffle slices are a must if you ask me and the lines are worth it for these slices.

name: Sam's Falafel
notes: Giant falafel sandwich that will leave you full for the rest of the day, definitely worth it! Staff is passionate and friendly, but I recommend taking the sandwich and walking over to the Hudson river and enjoy it watching the ships.

name: Leo's Bagel
notes: Great bagel spot in the Wall Street area: get one of their special bagels (I recommend the avocado and bacon). Simple but very filling!

name: Van Leeuwen Ice Cream
notes: Funky (always appreciated) flavors. I recommend their seasonal specials, the passion fruit was colorful and very tasty.

name: Pita Yeero
notes: Greek kiosk in an indoor food court: get the chicken gyro. Yummy!

name: Orale! Mexican Kitchen
notes: I've only ever ordered takeout from this Mexican spot, but the battered fish tacos and their rice side dish is something I go back to week after week.

name: Khiladi NYC
notes: Great dosa, I recommend the "everything" filling with cheese, potatoes and lentils.

name: Mariscos El Submarino
notes: Fish tacos in this small but very busy Queens Mexican restaurant.

name: Nada
notes: Vegan empanadas: warm and filling. The black bean and corn was great!

name: Spicy Moon
notes: Scallion pancakes and dan dan noodles in this vegan spot really hit the spot! Tasty and good portion sizes for our noodle cravings.

name: Taqueria Al Pastor
notes: Some of the tastiest tacos al pastor NYC has to offer. As always, the marinated pork, sauces and pinapple make for a great food experience. Props for being right outside of the subway stop.

name: Miss Ada
notes: Whipped ricotta + any other dish from this former Michelin spot that serves creative and super tasty Middle Eastern food.

name: For Five Coffee
notes: Great DC coffee! Their espresso was really good: bright and complex. A good afternoon coffee option for that post-lunch lethargic feeling.

name: Gregorys Coffee
notes: One of DC's best coffee shops: sit in their glass cubicles by the window watching the world go by having a snack and drinking a nice afternoon coffee.

name: George's King of Falafel and Cheesesteak
notes: Great shawarma: very filling and fresh!

name: The Exchange Saloon
notes: Nice bar with a cool rooftop overlooking DC: spot the airport and the National Mall.

name: Eye Street Grill
notes: Self-serve lunch restaurant. A lot of options, all tasty and healthy. Check it out when you're in the White House area.

name: Sunny Day
notes: Nice coffee kiosk at the corner of 23rd street.

name: Tov Coffee
notes: Turkish coffee in a double-decker bus decorated with Egyptian souvenirs.

name: Pajaro
notes: Small coffee shop: self-made plant milk, cute cups and very enthusiastic owner who loves to chat about coffee making.

name: Foode Cafe
notes: Sandwich shop with super friendly staff: get a Turkey & Havarti and enjoy it in a cozy and calm atmosphere.

name: Mirisata
notes: Great Sri Lankan food that is bursting with flavor in a very relaxed spot.

name: Dediko
notes: Cool spot for great Georgian food in sleepy Downtown Vancouver WA. Get the dumplings (khinkali) and cheese boat (khachapuri).

name: La Sorrentina
notes: Personal top 2 pizza spots in the US in the most random of locations, next to a largely empty business park and car lot. Some of the best Neapolitan pizza you can get.

name: Altengartz
notes: German food truck with very friendly owner cooking the bratwurst. Stick around to hear how his family has been running the truck for decades.

name: Mumbo Gumbo
notes: Great Cajun food served out of a funky food truck. The nipsey hussle is the perfect combo of fried shrimp, garlic butter and cajun spices.

name: Viking Soul Food
notes: Norwegian goodies in a vintage food truck: try out the lefse and pickled eggs.

name: Vesta Coffee Roasters
notes: Good coffee in the Arts District: great for sitting down and planning your first day in Vegas. Minimalist decor + espresso comes in cute little tray.

name: Mothership
notes: Great coffee hidden behind a neighbor's market and next to a live music amphitheater. Bonus for quirky sculptures at the entrance and for neighborly vibes.

name: The Writer's Block
notes: Coffee shop and bookstore in one: get a coffee drink, browse the books or listen in to the cafe's literary events.

name: Gordon Ramsay Burgers
notes: World famous burgers living up to the hype: skip the lines, get your order as takeout and sit outside people-watching on the Strip.

name: Golden Roast
notes: A delightful haven of superb coffee within the UT campus, both easily reachable and delectable.

name: Frothy Monkey, Downtown
notes: The perfect blend of excellent coffee, tasteful decor, and a welcoming atmosphere conducive to both work and dining.

name: French Market Creperie
notes: While the coffee is passable, the diverse and enticing crepe selection steals the show.

name: Coffee and Chocolate
notes: Known for heavenly chocolate cookies and the rare perk of being open until 10 pm, this cafe is a must-visit.

name: HoneyBee Coffee Co
notes: An ideal indoor locale for productive work sessions, casual gatherings, and coffee rendezvous.

name: Jacks Coffee and Plants
notes: An urban retreat offering more than just coffee - also a charming spot to buy plants in the heart of the city.

name: Spice and Tea Exchange
notes: An olfactory paradise offering an immense range of teas and spices, all available for a pre-purchase sniff.

name: Wild Love Bakehouse
notes: A sanctuary for coffee and croissant lovers, with the added charm of indoor and outdoor seating.

name: Mahalo Coffee Roasters
notes: Experience the magic of a couple-run caf√© (with interesting backstory) delivering sublime lattes.

name: Capycabara Coffee
notes: A welcoming spot featuring a friendly, well-versed staff, in a prime location with an adorable aesthetic.

name: Old City Java
notes: Immerse yourself in an environment of great vibes, excellent coffee, and versatile seating options, both indoors and outdoors.

name: Bida Saigon
notes: Delicious Pho, brimming with irresistible Vietnamese culinary delights.

name: Aroma Indian Kitchen
notes: The destination for scrumptious masala dosa and biryani, though the mutton offerings fall short of expectations.

name: The Tomato Head
notes: A trendy American pizzeria, dishing up a mix of vegetarian options, paired with a curated selection of beer and wine.

name: Kafiex Roasters
notes: Good coffee and a nice collection of books on the history of coffee and coffee culture.

name: Krays Coffee and Bakery
notes: Nice coffee and their parfaits are amazing!

name: Compass Coffee
notes: Good place to work or hangout with friends. Also has an outdoor patio.

name: Keeper Coffee
notes: Cozy but bustling! If you're lucky enough, you will get coffee from Morgan, world barista champion.

name: Foode Catering
notes: A delicious sandwich place with good coffee.

name: Relevant Coffee
notes: Spacious cafe with interesting group of goers. Great place to read a book, finish a project, or just have some philosophical chat with friends relaxing on the couch.

name: Case Study Coffee Roasters
notes: Fine inner decor. Good crowd of people; I was inspired to read.

name: Brewed Awakenings
notes: I love this cafe for its variety of seating. You will meet groups plaing board games, high schoolers doing homework, people with headphones, and people reading. Big menu; more than coffee.

name: Bollywood Theater
notes: Good collection of Indian street food. Not spicy but full of flavours.
